The samples were generated with: https://github.com/acecebov/SharpGLTF/blob/features/Issue116_Examples/tests/SharpGLTF.ThirdParty.Tests/AceCebovTests.cs

- ColorMorphing.glb morphs RED color to GREEN color (vertices also morph +1 in X to notice that the actual animation is running);

- TextureMorphing.glb morphs texture of the triangle. In start 3 vertices of triangle have different UV (pointing to diff colors), then with morphing they all end up in UV (1, 1) so should have same color (vertices also morph +1 in X to notice that the actual animation is running);

- ColorAndTextureMorphing morphs both color and texture. It starts with all 3 vertices with white color and same UV as in previous sample, then it morphs to color (0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5) and all UVs morph to same (1, 1).

Often, libraries will transpile their code when building with something like Babel to a version (often via browser targets) to ensure compliance, with further transpilation left to user-land. This is what R3F's babel config looks like, for example:

```js
// https://github.com/pmndrs/react-three-fiber/blob/master/babel.config.js
module.exports = {
  plugins: [],
  presets: [
    [
      '@babel/preset-env',
      {
        include: [
          '@babel/plugin-proposal-optional-chaining',
          '@babel/plugin-proposal-nullish-coalescing-operator',
          '@babel/plugin-proposal-numeric-separator',
          '@babel/plugin-proposal-logical-assignment-operators',
        ],
        bugfixes: true,
        loose: true,
        modules: false,
        targets: '> 1%, not dead, not ie 11, not op_mini all',
      },
    ],
    // These are because R3F uses React & TS
    // '@babel/preset-react',
    // '@babel/preset-typescript',
  ],
}
```

This can get tricky for things like examples/jsm, which can't easily be generated. I've hinted at transpiling examples/addons in https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/pull/23368#discussion_r794702220, but tree-shaking examples seem to be a blocker for the time being (related: #23372, should probably centralize this issue to solicit contribution).

In any case, having the linter pick this up should keep syntax in check.

