This bug is back 😬 because [the fix provided](https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/pull/23724) has been [removed in this commit](https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/pull/24453/commits/16d6c702edac79b20afb8ea2b65a8e1701e0396c#diff-c1dd4865c519271fcfbc0edc7f537658d0e1aa517cef9aff618fcd7294f901ddL70-L79) (see `WebGLNodeBuilder.js`).
And that fix was just a workaround anyway, it did not fix the problem [directly where it is](https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/blame/9d6c37f6acfd62672fd1343b9d7a028142c6af8d/examples/jsm/nodes/materials/NodeMaterial.js#L19).

Let me illustrate what is happening (just to be clear):

```js
class NodeMaterial {
  constructor() {
    this.type = this.constructor.name;
  }
}

class MySpecialMaterial extends NodeMaterial {
  // ...
}

const resultA = new NodeMaterial();
const resultB = new MySpecialMaterial();

console.log(resultA.type); // will output: "NodeMaterial", ✅ good
console.log(resultB.type); // will output: "MySpecialMaterial", ❌ bad !
```

(PS: `constructor.name` is also used [here](https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/blame/9d6c37f6acfd62672fd1343b9d7a028142c6af8d/examples/jsm/nodes/core/Node.js#L23-L27), but this one doesn't seem to have any side effects (in my project at least))

> no extended `Node` or `Material` should use a `type` other than the name of the class that builds it

Agreed, this is exactly my point ! 😅  and why I think [fixing it like this](https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/pull/24723/commits/3a1f022f78fb3b0cde1da2f479c3b85558690edb) is not the proper solution.

Let me explain:
During the class construction phase, if you set the type with `this.type = this.constructor.name;`, **it will be wrong** after instanciation (in the context of an extended class, like my `MySpecialMaterial` example above), up until the `WebGLNodeBuilder._parseShaderLib()` method get called during the [Material.onBuild()](https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/blob/9cfb9790cafcd9728800d4392b4b9d6fe16a6746/examples/jsm/renderers/webgl/nodes/WebGLNodes.js#L13) phase. This creates an invisible coupling that can cause a lot of unpredictable problems, like what just happened: someone remove that piece of code that fixes the type value, and things unexpectedly break elsewhere. Other problems could arise if an other piece of code checks the value of `material.type` (because it still have an invalid value, it's only "fixed" inside of `_parseShaderLib()`).

It would be much more solid and predictable to define the type this way:

```js
class LineBasicNodeMaterial extends NodeMaterial {
	constructor() {
		this.type = 'LineBasicNodeMaterial';
	}
}

class PointsNodeMaterial extends NodeMaterial {
	constructor() {
		this.type = 'PointsNodeMaterial';
	}
}

class MeshPhysicalNodeMaterial extends NodeMaterial {
	constructor() {
		this.type = 'MeshPhysicalNodeMaterial';
	}
}

// ...etc
```

There is no invisible coupling there, no unpredictable side effects, etc.

This is generated automatically and the way it is serialized, I wouldn't want to leave a "short blanket" here and solve one thing and leave another aside, the current approach meets both demands. `type` is always the class that built it so you can use `isNodeMaterial` to check if it's an extended class.

You shouldn't have problems with `Node` because its architecture is already updated, did you imagine how many extra strings we will have to add for each node following this model? Besides being something else for the user to worry about that they really shouldn't since we can get check the class extended with `.isNode` which is much more efficient and we should also think about doing procedurally.

If you need a provisional workaround still you can added:

```js
class MySpecialMaterial extends MeshPhysicalNodeMaterial {
	get type() {
		return 'MeshPhysicalNodeMaterial';
	}
}
```

By doing so you will not be able to deserialize this.

