You might want to look at what I would suggest first.  I did some digging on the FBX file format in regards to the `InnerAngle` and `OuterAngle` properties related to a spotlight defined in the file.  I believe now that the existing `FBXLoader.js` code has those two properties being used in an inverted manner compared to their intended use.  In other words, the two field names should be swapped with each other.  For example the current `FBXLoader` code assigns the `InnerAngle` to the `THREE.SpotLight` cone angle, when the `OuterAngle` should be used instead.  

I say this because of what I found in these FBX documents:

---

FBX Docs  URLs

If you read the first document you will see the legacy field names for `InnerAngle` and `OuterAngle`, which used to be `HotSpot` and `ConeAngle`.  This document defines ConeAngle as the outer angle, which is why it was renamed to OuterAngle later.  It defines HotSpot as the inner angle, which is why it was renamed to InnerAngle later:

https://download.autodesk.com/us/fbx/sdkdocs/fbx_sdk_help/files/fbxsdkref/class_k_fbx_light.html

This doc confirms the meaning of the InnerAngle and OuterAngle properties:

http://docs.autodesk.com/FBX/2014/ENU/FBX-SDK-Documentation/index.html?url=files/GUID-8EA6A733-8B78-4698-85A7-F19F426E9DD1.htm,topicNumber=d30e2057

Therefore the `OuterAngle` value should be assigned to the `THREE.SpotLight` _angle_ parameter, and then you have to derive the `penumbra` value from the ratio of the FBX `InnerAngle` and `OuterAngle` field values.

Because of this, I would restructure the code as shown below.  You tell me if you still want me to submit a PR.  Note, before I did that, I would require an FBX that has a spotlight defined in it to test this code, since this could is _not_ tested:

---

```js
// The default outer angle for the spotlight is 45 degrees,
//  expressed in radians because that is the format that
//  ThreeUS uses.
let angle = Math.PI / 4;

// Does the FBX file define an OuterAngle?
if ( lightAttribute.OuterAngle !== undefined ) {

    // Yes, the FBX file has a defined outer angle value,
    // so we should use it as the light cone angle.  
    // Limit the value to a value between 0 and 180 degrees.
    const angleDegrees = Math.max( 0, Math.min( 180, lightAttribute.OuterAngle.value ) );

    // Convert the value to radians because that is
    // the format ThreeJS uses.
    angle = THREE.MathUtils.degToRad( angleDegrees );
}

// ThreeJS expresses the penumbra as a percentage
//  of the angle value for the spotlight.  We set
//  the default value for the penumbra to 50%.  With
//  this value, as you move away from the light
//  cone's center , the light starts decaying at the
//  halfway point of the cone's radius.
let penumbra = 0.5;

// Does the FBX file define an InnerAngle value and
//  is that value less than the defined OuterAngle?
if ( lightAttribute.InnerAngle !== undefined
        && lightAttribute.OuterAngle !== undefined // A declared inner angle is only valid if the FBX file declared an outer angle.
        && lightAttribute.OuterAngle.value >= 0 // A negative inner angle is not valid.
        && lightAttribute.OuterAngle.value > 0 // This is to avoid a divide by zero error below.
        && lightAttribute.InnerAngle.value <= lightAttribute.OuterAngle.value // An inner angle that is greater than the outer angle is invalid.
    ) {

    // Yes, the FBX file has a defined inner angle value.
    //  Determine the penumbra percentage by finding
    //  the ratio between the inner and outer angle
    //  values defined in the FBX file, and subtracting
    //  that value from 1 to find the percentage of the
    //  light cone that should be part of the penumbra.
    let rawPenumbra = 1 - ( lightAttribute.InnerAngle.value / lightAttribute.OuterAngle.value );

    // This should not be necessary given the logic constraints
    //  encoded in the statements above, but we explicitly limit
    //  the value to the mandated range of 0 and 1 for
    //  the penumbra just in case.
    penumbra = Math.max(0, Math.min(1, rawPenumbra))
}
```

