I believe this is possible, but I'm not sure exactly what hooks would need to run in what order. This would take some testing to confirm, or @takahirox may know. 

The easiest option might be:

```javascript
const { scene, parser } = new GLTFLoader().loadAsync( 'path/to/scene.glb' );

for (const texture of await parser.getDependencies( 'texture' )) {

  texture.anisotropy = 4;

}
```

I believe that should work in the general case, returning one texture for each `.textures` entry in the glTF file. However it fails when `KHR_texture_transform` is used, as this clones and generates additional variants of those textures.

The `parser.associations` Map is supposed to have all textures in it, too. It currently misses those created by `KHR_texture_transform` as well but that is something we could fix.

I think other loaders have the same problem, don't they? If so, it may be good if we have a solution that is not `GLTFLoader` specific.

