Have you tried queuing your canvas export so it happens in isolation of frame rendering ?  Might be a bit more compatible with all libraries, runs outside of the animation loop, etc.  You don't have to worry about it being locked, blocked, or corrupted.

Pseudo Code and Notes:

```js
// controllable promise utility file

// make request and cancel generic to support most browsers
const idleOptions = { timeout: 500 };
const request = window.requestIdleCallback || window.requestAnimationFrame;
const cancel = window.cancelIdleCallback || window.cancelAnimationFrame;


// controllable promise
const resolveWhenIdle = {
  request: request,
  cancel: cancel,
  promise: (num) => new Promise((resolve) => request(resolve, Object.assign({}, idleOptions, num))),
};

export { resolveWhenIdle };
```

This is an example of a controllable `promise` which will slide itself in between rendered frames of any library.  It's setup to work in browsers with and without `requestAnimationFrame`. Whatever RAF function or library you use will boil down to this.

I use it to avoid blocking my render loop when I need a delay.  You can modify it get a shot at canvas within a reasonable amount of time from button click ensuring the previous frame has fully rendered.  No reference to any library, you just export the canvas contents as if everything has been paused.

For example: I want something to happen after a minimum 50 ms delay, on a complete frame boundary:

```js
// my usage when sequencing animations with delays on frame boundaries without blocking renders.
await resolveWhenIdle.promise( 50 );

// continue with code that needs to be executed on a frame boundary, in a timely manner, independent of framerate.
```

For your use case, this is what I would look at.

```js
// use 'then' or 'finally' knowing you allowed enough time to ensure any frame rendering in progress has completed
// and you have queued to run synchronously outside of whatever library is being used for rendering to the canvas element.
await resolveWhenIdle.promise( 50 ).finally( exportHTMLCanvasObjectContents() );
```

